Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cathcart, City of Glasgow, Lanark, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Cathcart, Glasgow, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1278–":"about 1278–Deceased","1280–Female":"1280–Deceased","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1278–Male":"1278–Deceased","Abt 1278":"about 1278","1278":"1278","Abt 1308":"about 1308","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ayr, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cathcart, City of Glasgow, Lanark, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Cathcart, Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern and eastern England): variant of   Carlton  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted in Northern Ireland as an Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cairealláin</b>, see   Carolan   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlton","meanings":["English (northern and eastern England): habitational name from any of various places called Carlton (Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Durham, Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Northamptonshire, Suffolk, East Yorkshire, Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire) or Carleton (Cumberland, Lancashire, Norfolk, Yorkshire). All come from Old Norse <i>karl</i> ‘common man, peasant’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’ (compare   Charlton  ). Places spelled <i>Carl(e)ton</i> (as opposed to <i>Charlton</i>) are in areas of Scandinavian settlement, mostly in northern England.","Irish (Antrim): variant of   Carleton   2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Carleton was born about 1278, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs William Carleton."},"et":{"Abt 1278–":"umbes 1278–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1308–Female":"1308–Surnud","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","Abt 1278":"umbes 1278","1278":"1278","Abt 1308":"umbes 1308","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ayr, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cathcart, City of Glasgow, Lanark, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Cathcart, Glasgow, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1278–":"noin 1278–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1308–Female":"1308–Kuollut","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","Abt 1278":"noin 1278","1278":"1278","Abt 1308":"noin 1308","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ayr, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cathcart, City of Glasgow, Lanark, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Cathcart, Glasgow, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1278–":"environ 1278–Décédé","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1308–Female":"1308–Décédée","1278–Male":"1278–Décédé","Abt 1278":"environ 1278","1278":"1278","Abt 1308":"environ 1308","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ayr, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Cathcart, City of Glasgow, Lanark, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Cathcart, Glasgow, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Carleton est né environ 1278, à Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Mrs William Carleton."},"de":{"Abt 1278–":"um 1278–Verstorben","1280–Female":"1280–Verstorben","1308–Female":"1308–Verstorben","1278–Male":"1278–Verstorben","Abt 1278":"um 1278","1278":"1278","Abt 1308":"um 1308","130